                <fr:title text="Bolza Problem">Bolza Problem</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
    Bolza problem is a fundamental formulation in the calculus of variations and optimal control that minimizes a cost functional consisting of both an integral term (running cost) and a terminal cost <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[J := \int _0^{t_f} L \big (\mathbf {x}(t), \mathbf {u}(t)\big ) dt + \Phi  \left ( \mathbf {x}(t_f) \right )]]></fr:tex> where state <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x}(t)\in  \mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>, control <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {u}(t)\in  \mathbb {R}^k]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L:\mathbb {R}^n \times  \mathbb {R}^k \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is the running cost and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi :\mathbb {R}^n \to  \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> is the terminal cost. The goal is to find the optimal control <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {u}^*(t)\in  \mathbb {R}^k]]></fr:tex> that minimizes this cost functional subject to the system dynamics and boundary conditions.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
